1 Introduction

Body mass index(BMI) is an important variable in determing how healthy an indivdual is and is affected by such variables as diet and exercise. The following report will through stastical analysis answer the questions of intrest:

  1. Has the body mass index (BMI) in Scotland changed over the given years of the Scottish Health Survey?

  2. Are there any differences in the BMI distribution by age, gender, socio-economic status or lifestyle factors?

2 Exploratory Analysis

Mean,Median and standard deviation of BMI by year
Year Mean Median Standard deviation
2016 28.03 27.28 5.79
2015 28.02 27.26 5.53
2014 27.84 27.17 5.21
2013 27.81 27.08 5.28

Therefore we can clearly see that the mean and median BMI has slightly increased over the years from 2013-2016. We can also see that the variation has also slightly increased from 2014-2016.

We can therefore see from the boxplots that there is a slight increase in BMI over the years and that the normality assumption is not vaild due to the number of outliers in the data.

2.1 Analyzing BMI Distribution by Different Factors

2.1.1 Age

From FigureÂ 1 we can see that there is a weak linear relation between age and BMI.

This weak relation tells that there is a small negative effect of the Age on the BMI.

2.1.2 Gender

From FigureÂ 2 we can see that greater variability in BMI among females compared to males,however having the same median indicates that while central tendency is similar, BMI distribution differs between genders. The normality assumption may not be satisfied due to the outliers in the boxplots.

2.1.3 Education

From FigureÂ 3 we can see that the small different in medians suggest a minor impact of education on BMI. However the variation on boxplots spreads,indicates that higher education levels might be associated with lower BMI variability. The normality assumption may not be satisfied due to outliers in the data.

2.1.4 Fruit and Veg

From FigureÂ 4 since both fruit and vegetarian have similar boxplots and median,it suggest that neither of them significantly effect BMI distribution. This indicates that BMI is similar regardless of whether a person having a fruit or vegetable. The normality assumption may not be satisfied due to outliers in the data.

3 Formal Analysis

3.1 Question 1

To determine whether BMI has changed in Scotland over the given years, we fit a regression model, where BMI is our outcome variable y and Year is our categorical variable x :

parsnip model object


Call:
stats::lm(formula = BMI ~ Year, data = data)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)     Year2014     Year2015     Year2016  
   27.81034      0.02872      0.21339      0.22322
Model output of BMI against year
Intercept Year2014 Year2015 Year2016
27.81034 0.02872 0.21339 0.22322

We can interpret the estimates as follows: Intercept: This tells us that when the year is 2013 the BMI of an individual is expected to be 27.81034.

Year2014: This tells us that when the year is 2014 there is an associated an increase of,on average of 0.02872 in BMI of an individual.

Year2015: This tells us that when the year is 2015 there is an associated an increase of,on average of 0.21339 in BMI of an individual.

Year2016: This tells us that when the year is 2016 there is an associated an increase of,on average of 0.22322 in BMI of an individual.

We can use the estimates obtained here to fit our regression equation as follows:

\[ BMI = \alpha + \beta_{2014}\cdot I_{2014}(x) +\beta_{2015}\cdot I_{2015}(x)+\beta_{2016}\cdot I_{2016}(x) \]

where

  • the intercept \(\alpha\) is the mean BMI for our baseline year, 2013;

  • \(\beta_{year}\) is the difference in the mean BMI in a given year relative to the baseline year 2013; and

  • \(I_{year}(x)\) is an indicator function such that

    \[ I_{year}(x) = \left\{ \begin{array}{rcl}\ 1 & \mbox{if x matches the given year} \\ 0 & \mbox{otherwise} \end{array}\right. \]

We can now assess the fit of our model.

We first do this by obtaining residuals. These are then plotted by year to test our assumptions:

FigureÂ 5 shows that the residuals are evenly spread and have mean zero. Therefore our assumption of constant variance appears to be valid.

We next plot a histogram to check that the residuals are normally distributed:

FigureÂ 6 shows that the residuals are centered at zero and are bell shaped. Therefore our assumption of normality appears to be valid. ## Question 2

4 Conclusions

In conclusion, the analysis of BMI in Scotland from 2013 to 2016 shows only slight difference over the years,indicating a stability in BMI levels during this period.

Regarding BMI distribution differences based on sex, age, education, and dietary habits, the interaction model highlights important variations. BMI tends to be higher in older individuals and males, while those with higher education levels generally have lower BMI.

The interaction effects reveal complex relationships between these factors, showing how multiple variables jointly influence BMI distribution.
